\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Homeworks Heap
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Plasencia Palacios Milton Nicolas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1) Some stuff about the time insert vs build heap.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
6.1-7) To show that the leave nodes are indexed using 
\begin_inset Formula $\lfloor\frac{n}{2}\rfloor+1,\lfloor\frac{n}{2}\rfloor+2,\ldots n$
\end_inset

 we must prove that those nodes does not have a left or right child, so,
 given an index 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$i$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$i 
\backslash
in $
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $[\lfloor\frac{n}{2}\rfloor+1,\lfloor\frac{n}{2}\rfloor+2,\ldots n]$
\end_inset

, by taking 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$i=$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\lfloor\frac{n}{2}\rfloor+1$
\end_inset

, we can write its left child as 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$2i=$
\end_layout

\end_inset

2
\begin_inset Formula $\lfloor\frac{n}{2}\rfloor+2>n$
\end_inset

, but it cannot be because our heap is made up by at most n nodes.
 So the other values in the interval, which are greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $\lfloor\frac{n}{2}\rfloor+1$
\end_inset

, cannot have a left child (and also a right child), then those are leave
 nodes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
6.2-6) Considering a max-heap in which the elements 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$i 
\backslash
in 
\backslash
{1, 
\backslash
, 2,  
\backslash
cdots 100
\backslash
}$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (so the repetitions are not allowed), and we have the heap build sucht
 that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$i=1$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the root.
 By applying heapify we must call it at every level of the heap, which has
 height 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
log n$
\end_layout

\end_inset

, so the worst case will have time complexity 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
Omega(
\backslash
log n)$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
6.3-3) Given a n nodes Binary-Heap we can say that the leave nodes are 
\begin_inset Formula $\lceil\frac{n}{2}\rceil=\lceil\frac{n}{2^{0+1}}\rceil$
\end_inset

.
 We can prove the thesis by induction, so we assume that, at the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$h-1$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 level, the equation holds.
 At the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$h$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 level 
\end_layout

